Which simply in modern language we can translate it as a fate of information

49:53.000 --> 49:59.000
So in that sense evolution can occur in any system whether information transfers from one generation to the next

49:59.000 --> 50:01.000
As long as you have some sort of replicating system

50:01.000 --> 50:07.000
So human culture, it adds to it, just adds to the new mechanism of information, transparent modification

50:07.000 --> 50:09.000
Which is through our culture

50:09.000 --> 50:14.000
And because that method is quite radically different, you can transfer information only to the next generation

50:14.000 --> 50:18.000
But kind of laterally, almost like bacteria do with their lateral gene transfer

50:18.000 --> 50:22.000
You can recover lost information from the past and there are old sorts of ways

50:22.000 --> 50:26.000
How can fresh can be transferred in ways that are not found in biological systems

50:26.000 --> 50:30.000
It certainly lends to some novelty and intentionality as part of it as well

50:30.000 --> 50:34.000
Some creative intent of individuals, so we should not discount those as well

50:34.000 --> 50:39.000
But at a higher level of maybe higher social structures within the human society

50:39.000 --> 50:45.000
There is some element of maybe not necessarily selection because I don't want to draw analogy to like

50:45.000 --> 50:48.000
Fitness in biological systems, I think it would be too

50:48.000 --> 50:50.000
Maybe too untrue

50:50.000 --> 50:58.000
But there is some sort of sorting, you have variance and they are being by some either random function or maybe not

50:58.000 --> 51:01.000
They are being sorted and distributed where some persist some do not

51:01.000 --> 51:03.000
In that sense it does hold

51:03.000 --> 51:09.000
