52:02.000 --> 52:07.000
Based on the frequency of the letters and the two and three letter combinations

52:07.000 --> 52:10.000
To minimise finger motion

52:10.000 --> 52:16.000
But we are all locked into the QWERTY keyboard which was designed to make us type slowly

52:16.000 --> 52:18.000
Because the machines would jam

52:18.000 --> 52:23.000
And C-Mingigal has a lovely essay about this, in evolution

52:23.000 --> 52:29.000
It doesn't have to be optimal, it just has to work and then it gets fixed and stuck

52:29.000 --> 52:33.000
And so every time we look at your computer, you should think

52:33.000 --> 52:38.000
My god, this is an icon of how brilliant we are and how stupid we are

52:38.000 --> 52:41.000
Because the keyboard is literally pretty stupid

52:41.000 --> 52:47.000
In biology, they talk about the... not optimising but satisfying

52:47.000 --> 52:50.000
So anyway, that's...

52:50.000 --> 52:53.000
And this is probably very true to human culture as well

52:53.000 --> 52:58.000
Something that might persist for reasons other than being the best serving the needs

52:58.000 --> 53:04.000
So for instance, some years ago I embarked on a project trying to apply biological methods

53:04.000 --> 53:10.000
Maybe very naively trying to reconstruct the phylogeny kind of evolutionary tree of musical instruments

53:10.000 --> 53:15.000
We discovered very unusual and interesting patterns that we had to do with looking at coordinates

53:15.000 --> 53:18.000
From the late 19th century and up to the middle of the 20th century

53:18.000 --> 53:23.000
And it turned out that some of the trumpet related musical instruments

53:23.000 --> 53:30.000
And it turns out that some of the trans that we found had to do not specifically with a better design of vowels

53:30.000 --> 53:33.000
And the way horn is structured overall

53:33.000 --> 53:39.000
But there were some purely economic reasons for developing the industry in some ways

53:39.000 --> 53:43.000
Because some people patented certain ways of making it

53:43.000 --> 53:46.000
Preventing other people from doing it, there were other social forces

53:46.000 --> 53:51.000
Had nothing to do with optimising a particular item

53:51.000 --> 53:54.000
Obviously humanly designed in a very creative way

53:54.000 --> 53:57.000
Item that was very consciously designed, but it could only develop in certain ways

53:57.000 --> 54:01.000
Because higher level social structures like patent agencies

54:01.000 --> 54:06.000
And maybe some individual players, some jazz players that used some of these instruments

54:06.000 --> 54:09.000
They preferred something more artistic

54:09.000 --> 54:13.000
And they designed purely for aesthetic and historical reasons

54:13.000 --> 54:17.000
They didn't really care about maybe a better playability in some ways

54:17.000 --> 54:25.000
So there are many more, I think, aspects to human ways of variations being sorted in human culture

54:25.000 --> 54:30.000
That's why I didn't want to define it as a specific fitness function

54:30.000 --> 54:32.000
Because fitness applies only to one thing

54:32.000 --> 54:42.000
This is an interesting thing to bring into it

54:42.000 --> 54:46.000
But when you start talking about fitness

54:46.000 --> 54:50.000
It's very easy to say when you're talking about Darwinian evolution

54:50.000 --> 54:52.000
And even neo-Darwinian evolution

54:52.000 --> 54:55.000
What the sort of goal is, you don't really need a goal

54:55.000 --> 55:00.000
It's just those entities that do a better job of propagating themselves

55:00.000 --> 55:03.000
But when we get to cultural evolution

55:03.000 --> 55:05.000
Then you do have to start saying, well, what is the goal?

55:05.000 --> 55:11.000
What do we want? It's not necessarily true that the goal is for each of us to have as many offspring as we want

55:11.000 --> 55:15.000
In fact, we're starting to realize that there's a whole other level of planetary fitness

55:15.000 --> 55:17.000
In which that's actually bad

55:17.000 --> 55:23.000
So you can't help but start to say, okay, so what really is the goal?

55:23.000 --> 55:28.000
But when you get to aesthetics, it's very interesting because you could say, well, this is something that

55:28.000 --> 55:30.000
Isn't really a part of biological evolution

55:30.000 --> 55:33.000
Except it is because you get into sexual selection

55:33.000 --> 55:38.000
And you get these ridiculous structures that are among the most useless

55:38.000 --> 55:41.000
And the most beautiful parts of nature

55:41.000 --> 55:44.000
Which have this whole other goal

55:44.000 --> 55:47.000
But it's still the same goal, but it's attracting a mate

55:47.000 --> 55:50.000
Not anything that's more useful for

55:50.000 --> 55:53.000
And they agree with you, especially when they mentioned earlier that it all comes down there

55:53.000 --> 55:59.000
So just the way human brain functions too, which I also don't have as much expertise to speculate about

55:59.000 --> 56:03.000
But, Linus Frost has one interesting comment

56:03.000 --> 56:09.000
When critiquing the purely biological transfer of the notions of evolution to the culture

56:09.000 --> 56:13.000
But the X doesn't reproduce, doesn't make another X

56:13.000 --> 56:17.000
So it happens to in the mind of its creator, conceiving the idea of it

56:17.000 --> 56:21.000
And what happens to these ideas, how they manifested in the objects

56:21.000 --> 56:25.000
So you can't necessarily even look at those coordinates and say, well, that's how they evolve

56:25.000 --> 56:33.000
Now they just maybe imperfect reflection of the processes that occur in the human brain

56:33.000 --> 56:35.000
And the evolution at that level

56:35.000 --> 56:39.000
So I think just looking at the cultural artifacts as such

56:39.000 --> 56:42.000
As divorced from the workings of the human mind

56:42.000 --> 56:47.000
I don't think it's a very legitimate pursuit in that way to view cultural evolution like that

56:47.000 --> 56:51.000
It's certainly just looking at organismal features

56:51.000 --> 56:57.000
Can allow you to reconstruct phylogeny, maybe in quite a precise way

56:57.000 --> 57:04.000
But it's not telling you the mechanism of how evolution further occurred through speciation variation

57:04.000 --> 57:08.000
So in that way, you can also tell something about the way human culture works

57:08.000 --> 57:13.000
By looking at some patterns of similarities between artifacts and different aspects of human culture

57:13.000 --> 57:18.000
But do you really understand that you really need to look at the function of the mind?

57:18.000 --> 57:24.000
I've been doing a lot of reading and research right now for a book I'm writing

57:24.000 --> 57:28.000
On how this applies to finance and economics and investing

57:28.000 --> 57:34.000
And one of the things that we all have these hunter-gatherer brains

57:34.000 --> 57:38.000
And we live in this incredibly advanced civilization

57:38.000 --> 57:48.000
But we're still on the psychological level, we have a lot in common with humans 10, 20, 30,000 years ago

57:48.000 --> 57:50.000
100,000 years ago

57:50.000 --> 57:55.000
And so our thinking is fast and slow, we're predictably irrational

57:55.000 --> 58:01.000
And we're driven by all kinds of variable hormones in our body

58:01.000 --> 58:11.000
And so there's another question, how did a complex global scientific civilization

58:11.000 --> 58:21.000
Possibly emerge from such stupid primates, some of whom are president of the United States recently?

58:21.000 --> 58:26.000
Well, I wonder, do you really think that we live in an incredibly advanced civilization?

58:26.000 --> 58:32.000
I think we have the potential to form one, but I would say that as a basic prerequisite

58:32.000 --> 58:39.000
To define an advanced civilization you would have to have the ability to imagine that

58:39.000 --> 58:45.000
You're sort of a part of a sustainable civilization, and I'm not sure we're actually there yet

58:45.000 --> 58:52.000
I mean, there's the normative moral side of it, and then there's just the fact of it

58:52.000 --> 58:59.000
And I'm just talking about the fact that our world is so different than when people lived in 100 years ago or 1000 years ago

58:59.000 --> 59:15.000
I agree with that, but I also think that it's possible that, I mean, trying to describe Manhattan to say one of the 100 gatherers who lived at a pinnacle point

59:15.000 --> 59:23.000
One of the most important things that we have to do is to imagine that we have a 100,000 years ago

59:23.000 --> 59:30.000
Which may have been among the first homo sapiens sapiens in southern tip of Africa would be very difficult

59:30.000 --> 59:38.000
Humans have an amazing ability, capacity for reinvention, they were probably genetically pretty similar to us

59:38.000 --> 59:44.000
But maybe that's more stuffed now, yeah, but maybe that difficulty of them imagining our world is as difficult as it is for us to imagine what an advanced civilization would be like

59:44.000 --> 59:51.000
So, yeah, do you think that how long before we get there, I'd like to know?

59:51.000 --> 59:57.000
Well, I want to see it, so when I hear you talk about speaking up and fasting

59:57.000 --> 01:00:03.000
When I hear you talk about these levels, Adam's simple cells complex of...

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:08.000
One question that I can't help but wondering is, okay, what's next? The next level

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:16.000
I read something recently actually when I was just starting to write my book that I just finished by Isaac Asimov written in the 70s

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:25.000
Just a little short essay where he talked about this hierarchy of atoms to molecules to viruses to full-blown cells to multi-cellular

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:34.000
And then he talks about the multi-organismic and there's some examples of sort of full-blown superorganisms like insect colonies and so forth

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:40.000
And then he talked about we humans, we have leanings towards that superorganism

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:44.000
We have some identity with the tribe, with the group, but we're not quite there, we're still

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:56.000
And to me that was really powerful, like I thought, and I say the beginning of my life, yeah, well in a certain way we're stuck between the individual and the superorganism

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:05.000
In a way, that's one way of encapsulating our predicament here as human beings trying to have a sustainable society because there are ways in which we need to function as a superorganism

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:08.000
But we're not inherently good at that

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:20.000
So I found that powerful because it's just one way of trying to place our current cultural difficulties in the context of what we're talking about here

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:26.000
Where do we fit, and what's next in that? I'm really scared of that analogy

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:31.000
I don't want to be part of a superorganism

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:41.000
Cells, unicellular organisms were looking out for themselves, and in multi-cellular organisms the individual cells are easily expendable

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:53.000
They can be sacrificed quite regularly for the good of the... and I don't want to live in that in a society that's going to throw a bunch of us away

01:01:53.000 --> 01:02:01.000
I don't think that's going to be progress, right? There's going to be progress when every person, nobody lives in poverty

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:07.000
When people have the resources are more or less spread much more equally than they are

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:12.000
And everybody has dignity and everybody has access to decent things

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:15.000
That doesn't look like a superorganism to me

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:19.000
It looks like a rationally designed system, right?

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:23.000
And again, rationality, it's kind of important when rationality gets in the game

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:27.000
