01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:17.000
Maybe...

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:18.000
Eliminating poverty...

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:23.000
I mean, this is why it's not strictly a biological step to go to the superorganism

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:28.000
If we're going to get into intentionality and rationality, maybe that's what's missing to...

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:30.000
to bring us to that next step

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:37.000
And evolution's just not predictive, and there's nothing strange about evolution leading a system into a complete disaster

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:43.000
But as you were saying, cultural evolution is different because we have these scenarios in our mind

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:47.000
And I think we're not thinking about the future enough as a...

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:51.000
Yes, making people smarter would be a really good idea

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:57.000
So one of the things that this little discussion brings to mind

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:02.000
The little discussion brings out is that we have all these values like human rights

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:05.000
And they're not written into nature

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:07.000
They're invented by humans

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:13.000
Or the traditional religious worldview is that they're dictated by a creator

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:16.000
That each human has innate value

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:24.000
And so the scientific and post-enlightenment world is trying to figure out how to ground concepts like human rights

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:28.000
Which is... it's a great invention, but it's a fiction

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:31.000
Just like money's a fiction, it's not really real

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:38.000
There's no other species, exchanges, matter, energy, and ingenuity based on symbolic systems about values

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:46.000
So one of the ways to ground...

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:58.000
Our intuitive sense of the innate value of human rights is in what Whitehead thought about, Alfred North Whitehead

01:04:58.000 --> 01:05:08.000
The idea that emerging complexity creates at every stage a greater freedom, greater possibility

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:12.000
And there are kind of thresholds

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:17.000
And that the human is a particularly intense threshold

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:22.000
In which the complexity of the cells in our body, the social networks

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:31.000
We're kind of a nexus of a lot of freedom, a lot of choice, a lot of possibility

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:36.000
I don't think morality is really an issue for other primates

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:38.000
So it is for us

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:43.000
I think that the planetary scale that could be to overcome our fears

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:48.000
That being subsumed and being less free could be more free

01:05:48.000 --> 01:05:52.000
Is that your personal hope or you think it could be even...

01:05:52.000 --> 01:05:56.000
In this sort of Whiteheadian metaphysics, there is a telos to the universe

01:05:56.000 --> 01:06:03.000
And that telos is a greater complexity, greater freedom, greater creativity

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:08.000
And greater beauty, for him beauty of aesthetics is an important point

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:13.000
So I think you can... it's not fully worked out

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:23.000
But I think you can start to define things that there is a real difference between killing bacteria versus killing humans

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:27.000
And there's a qualitative and quantitative difference

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:35.000
